{
  "id": "q-agent-payment-standard-choice",
  "question": "How should a Stellar API choose between x402, MPP, and other emerging agent-payment protocols without locking its application to one standard?",
  "surface": [
    "skills.stellar-dev.agentic-payments",
    "stellarDocs.search_docs"
  ],
  "golden": {
    "answer": "Choose by interaction and settlement model, then isolate it behind an adapter covering quote/payment intent, payment evidence, settlement, fulfillment, idempotency, and refunds. x402 V2 and MPP both use HTTP 402 but have different payloads and infrastructure; x402 V2 also has extensions, discovery, and session mechanisms, so it is not purely stateless. MPP Charge settles on-chain while Session uses a channel for repeated traffic. AP2 supplies authorization, mandate, and audit semantics that can sit above a rail; ACP is a beta commerce protocol for catalog, cart, checkout, and orders, not Stellar settlement. Cite each protocol's own specification and keep entitlement independent.",
    "keyFacts": [
      "x402 V2 and MPP are distinct HTTP-402 protocols with different payloads, settlement, and infrastructure; x402 V2 is not purely stateless.",
      "MPP Charge settles on-chain, while MPP Session uses cumulative off-chain channel commitments.",
      "AP2 supplies authorization/mandate/audit semantics above a rail; ACP is a beta commerce protocol, not Stellar settlement.",
      "A protocol adapter covers quote/payment intent, payment evidence, settlement, fulfillment, idempotency, and refunds."
    ],
    "avoid": [
      "x402, MPP, AP2, and ACP are interchangeable names for the same protocol.",
      "MPP always requires one on-chain transaction for every paid response."
    ],
    "notes": "Status-sensitive details are stated as of 2026-07-11; grade later sourced changes leniently and require dated primary evidence."
  },
